      <comment>r2.7.1) (robot Adding: [[sl:Ahmed I.]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Redirect|Ahmad I|others named Ahmed I and Ahmad I|Ahmad I (disambiguation)}}
{{Refimprove|date=November 2010}}
{{Infobox Ottoman sultan
 |Sultan_Name=Sultan Ahmed I
 |image_portrait=I Ahmet.jpg
 |image_tugra=Tughra of Ahmed I.JPG
 |Military=Growth of the Ottoman Empire
 |title=[[List of sultans of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Sultan]]|title2=[[Ottoman Caliphate|Caliph]]
 |before=[[Mehmed III]]
 |after=[[Mustafa I]]
 |years=1603&amp;ndash;1617}}
'''Ahmed I Bakhti''' ([[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]]: احمد اول ''Aḥmed-i evvel'', {{lang-tr|I.Ahmet}}) (April 18, 1590 &amp;nbsp;– November 22, 1617) was the [[Sultan]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] from 1603 until his death in 1617.

==Biography==
Ahmed I's mother was [[Valide Sultan]] [[Handan Sultan]], an ethnic [[Greeks|Greek]] who was originally named Helena. He was born at [[Manisa]] Palace. He succeeded his father [[Mehmed III]] (1595&amp;ndash;1603) in 1603 at age 13. He broke with the traditional fratricide and sent his brother Mustafa to live at the old palace at Bayezit along with their grandmother Safiye Sultan. He was known for his skills in fencing, poetry, horseback riding, and fluency in numerous languages.

In the earlier part of his reign Ahmed I showed decision and vigor, which were belied by his subsequent conduct. The wars which attended his accession both in [[Hungary]] and in [[Iran|Persia]] terminated unfavourably for the empire, and its prestige received its first check in the [[Treaty of Sitvatorok|Treaty of Zsitvatorok]], signed in 1606, whereby the annual tribute paid by [[Austria]] was abolished. [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Azerbaijan]] were ceded to Persia.

Ahmed was a poet who wrote a number of political and lyrical works under the name Bahti. He was devoutly religious, spending much of his wealth to support the works of scholars and pious men. He also attempted to enforce conformance to Islamic laws and traditions, restoring the old regulations that prohibited alcohol and he attempted to enforce attendance at the [[Friday Mosque]] prayers and paying alms to the poor in the proper way.  Ahmed I died of [[typhus]] in 1617.

==Legacy==
[[File:Savary Franco Ottoman Capitulations 1615.jpg|thumb|Bilingual Franco-Turkish translation of the 1604 [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|Franco-Ottoman Capitulations]] between Sultan Ahmed I and [[Henry IV of France]], published by [[François Savary de Brèves]] in 1615.&lt;ref name=&quot;Bosworth&quot;&gt;[http://books.google.com/books?id=PvwUAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PA799 ''The Encyclopaedia of Islam: Fascicules 111-112 : Masrah Mawlid'' by Clifford Edmund Bosworth p.799]&lt;/ref&gt;]]
Today Ahmed I is remembered mainly for the construction of the [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque]] (also known as the [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque|Blue Mosque]]), one of the masterpieces of [[Islamic architecture]]. The area in [[Istanbul]] around the Mosque is today called Sultanahmet. He died at [[Topkapı Palace]] in [[Istanbul]] and is buried in a mausoleum right outside the walls of the famous mosque.

He was married twice, to Valide Sultan [[Mahfiruze Hatice Sultan]], originally named Maria, a [[Greeks|Greek]], mother of [[Osman II]], and to Valide Sultan Kadinefendi [[Kösem Sultan]] or Mahpeyker, originally named Anastasia, a [[Greeks|Greek]], mother of [[Murad IV]] and [[Ibrahim I]]. He also had two sons named Bayezid and Suleiman.

==Rival to Ottoman Throne==
A half-brother of Amhed, [[Jahja]], resented his accession to the Ottoman throne in 1603, and spent his life scheming to become Sultan.

